# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1879-major-league-baseball-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The **1878 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1878, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the third season of the National League.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1877, two teams would fold: Brooklyn Hartfords and St.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] They were replaced by the Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Later in the offseason, the Providence Grays would join on February 6, raising the number of teams to seven.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] On April 1 or 2, the Louisville Grays would officially resign from the league, once again lowering the number of teams to six.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The 1878 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] This format had been in place since the previous season, and would be the final season which saw this format, due to expansion to eight teams the following season.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all six teams.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams hosted games at neutral sites, the Indianapolis Blues and Providence Grays.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Four tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues had three tie games.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Milwaukee Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings leave the 23rd Street Grounds (where they played for four seasons since their National Association days from 1874) and move to Lakefront Park where they would play for seven seasons through 1884.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-boston-red-caps-season] The **1879 Boston Red Caps season** was the ninth season of the franchise.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-buffalo-bisons-season] The 1879 season was the debut year in the National League for the **Buffalo Bisons**, who had previously played an independent schedule.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-buffalo-bisons-season] The Bisons wound up with a record of 46–32 and finished in third place.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1879 Chicago White Stockings season** was the eighth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fourth in the National League and the second at Lakefront Park.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 46–33.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1879 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fifth in the National League with a record of 43–37, 14 games behind the Providence Grays.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds were hoping to build off a great 1878 season, in which the team finished in second place in the National League with a 37–23 record.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In the off-season, the Reds announced that catcher Deacon White would become the player-manager.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Ross Barnes to play shortstop.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Barnes had missed most of the 1877 season and all of the 1878 season after falling ill.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In his last full season in 1876, Barnes played with the Chicago White Stockings, and led the NL with a .429 batting average, 138 hits, 126 runs, 38 doubles, and fourteen triples.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] King Kelly had a very solid season, hitting .348 with two home runs and 47 RBI, while another youngster, twenty-year-old Buttercup Dickerson, hit .291 with two home runs and a team high 57 RBI.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Deacon White rebounded from a poor 1878 season by his standards, as he hit .330 with a homer and 52 RBI.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, Will White led the NL with 75 starts, as he had a 43–31 record with a 1.99 ERA in his league high 680 innings pitched.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati started off hot, as they opened the season with a five-game winning streak.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] However, the club lost seven of their next eight games to fall under .500.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati had a mediocre 9–9 record after eighteen games, and player-manager Deacon White turned over his managerial duties to Cal McVey, who had been the Reds' player-manager in 1878.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati lost the first five games under McVey, however, the team began to play better, and ended the season with a 43–37 record, fifth in the league, and fourteen games behind the first-place Grays.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The **1879 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1879, and saw the Providence Grays as the pennant winner of the fourth season of the National League.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League was set on expanding from a six-team league to an eight-team league.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays folded, and in its place, the league admitted the Cleveland Blues, the International Association's Buffalo Bisons and Syracuse Stars, and finally (with confirmation Milwaukee was not returning) the Troy Trojans.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] It is suggested by Society for American Baseball Research (SABR) that this season featured the first African-American to play major league baseball, William Edward White, who played one game with the Providence Grays on June 21.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] He predates brothers Moses Fleetwood Walker and Weldy Walker by five years, and Jackie Robinson by 68 years.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The 1879 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 12-games-each format that had been in place since 1877, as the National League expanded from six to eight teams, adding 24 games to each team's schedule.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring six teams.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Five tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings had four tie games.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Reds, Providence Grays, and Syracuse Stars had one tie game each.
[src:1879-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at the Putnam Grounds on September 20 against the Chicago White Stockings, moving to Haymakers' Grounds for the start of the 1880 season.
